					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-552686#post-1956073</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-552686/scp-1535#post-1956073</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 04 Feb 2014 07:20:38 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Doctor GE Smith</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1786409</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Enthusiastic +1!<br /> 2 experimental thoughts:<br /> First, the article assumes death by asphyxiation based on the time in a sealed jar, but this could easily be checked, both by doing timed tests with varying species in an identical non-anomolous jar and by adding oxygen-releasing materials with the animal before sealing the lid and seeing if they extend lifespan.<br /> Second, there's got to be a limited number of inquisitors from Castille, and a slightly less limited number of collaborating individuals. I'd be surprised if the Foundation didn't keep using it until it ran through everybody to see if the list would loop back, and if second-timers remembered their first visit.<br /> I'm also left curious about origin. There's a historic and thematic disconnect between a 1946 glass mason jar and the Spanish Inquisition. My best supposition would be that it was a convenient container for the creator to use, and that they had a beef with inquisitions (probably something to do with having the ability to make anomolous objects).</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
